Use Tailwind's real scanner instead of the plugin's regex extractor.

The plugin extracted class candidates with a single regex whose charset
(builder.js: [a-zA-Z0-9_\-\/:.!\[\]#%]+) excludes parentheses, & and >. Measured
against the official CLI on identical markup: text-red-500, gap-3 and
data-selected:bg-black are emitted by both, but w-[calc(100%-2rem)],
bg-(--accent) and [&>p]:mt-2 are DROPPED by the plugin and emitted by the CLI.
The build stays green and the class stays in the HTML with no CSS behind it, so
the failure is silent. bg-(--token) is v4's idiomatic way to reference a design
token, so this is the common case rather than an edge.

@tailwindcss/oxide is the scanner the official CLI uses and is already an
installed dependency. Feeding it the compiler's own discovered @source patterns
gives byte-equivalent candidate extraction, and it understands arbitrary values,
arbitrary variants and the v4 paren shorthand.

The regex path, its glob helpers and the config.sources file-reading loop are
left in place for callers that pass explicit file paths; only the source-pattern
scan switches to the real scanner.

